40|$|This paper {{studies the}} {{strategy}} Morrison adopts in Beloved to {{give voice to}} <b>black</b> <b>Americans</b> long silenced by the dominant white American culture. Instead of being objects passively accepting their aphasia, <b>black</b> <b>Americans</b> become speaking subjects {{that are able to}} cast an oppositional gaze to avert the objectifying gaze of white Americans. Further, the novel as a whole becomes a voicing artifact that constitutes an oppositional gaze toward the silencing tendency upheld by the dominant white American culture. In this way, the <b>black</b> <b>Americans</b> manage to work out a strategy of collective coexistence in a white supremacist society. </p...|$|R
